data: The revenue (in units of Euro) from the sale of Widgets for a specified month, denoted $R_{\text{Month}}$, is given by the sum of the revenue produced from the three widgets ABX56, ABX66 and ABX76, of the specified month. That is:
The total revenue over these three months is the sum of these monthly total revenues, and so:

The percentage of total sales revenue generated in May, denoted $P_{\text{May}}$, is then given by the total revenue from the sales of Widgets in May ($R_{\text{May}}$) expressed as a percentage of the total revenue from the sale of Widgets across all three months ($R_{\text{Total}}$):

data: An order for 8 ABX56 widgets and 9 ABX66 widgets could not be processed in time and therefore could not be added to the June figures.
How much sales revenue would these 17 widgets have added?

For a given month, the price of a single widget, denoted $C_{\text{month}}^{\text{widget}}$, is given by the revenue made by that widget divided by the total number of sales of that widget for the specified month.
For the cases of ABX56 and ABX66 in June, we get:
So in June, the revenue made from 1 ABX56 widget was €15 and the revenue made from 1 ABX66 widget was €13.
Therefore, the revenue made from 8 ABX56 widgets is $8 \times €15 = €120$, and from 9 ABX66 widgets is $9 \times €13 = €117$.
The sale revenue generated by selling 8 units of ABX56 and 9 units of ABX66 in June is thus $€120+€117=€237$.

data: The cost of revenue for a single ABX76 widget (i.e. its unit price) in June was $\frac{480}{24}=20$ Euros.
If in July this unit price decreased by 20$\%$, this means that the unit price of an ABX76 widget in July, denoted $C_{\text{ABX76}}^{\text{July}}$, is:

The number of units of ABX76 sold in June is 24. If the sales increased by 25$\%$ from June to July, this means that the total number of units of ABX76 sold in July, denoted $N_{\text{ABX76}}^{\text{July}}$, is:

The total July sales revenue generated by the ABX76 widget (in Euros), denoted $R_{\text{ABX76}}^{\text{July}}$, is given by the total number of units sold multiplied by the cost of an individual sale, and so we get:

From 1985 to 1987, the number of fares collected for subways dropped by approximately what percent?

data: In 1985 the number of fares collected for subways was 350 million and in 1987 it was 260 million. The percentage increase in fare collections over this period, denoted $P_I$, is given by the increase in the number of fares collected from 1987 to 1985, expressed as a fraction over the initial number of fares collected (i.e. fares collected in 1985). That is:

So we see that there was a percentage increase of -25$\%$ from 1985 to 1987. The negative sign indicated a percentage decrease, and so to the nearest percent, we get that the percentage decrease in fares collected from 1985 to 1987 was 25$\%$.

If in 1984 the average subway fare collected was 50 cents and the average bus fare collected was 30 cents, then the ratio of the total dollar amount of subway fares collected to the total dollar amount of bus fares was approximately.

data: In 1984, there were 350 million subway fares collected, and 310 million bus fares collected.
Given the average subway fare collected was 50 cents = \$0.5, the total dollar amount of subway fares collected was:
$$\$0.5 \times 350 \times 10^6 = \$175 \times 10^6.$$
Similarly, given the average bus fare collected was 30 cents = \$$0.3, the total dollar amount of bus fares collected was:
$$\$0.3 \times 310 \times 10^6 = \$93 \times 10^6.$$
The required ratio is therefore:
Now, to compare this solution to the possible answers we will multiply both sides of the ratio by the value of the first position of each ratio in the solutions. Doing so, we get:
Comparing these ratios to the ratios of the solutions, we see that to the nearest whole number the ratio is approximately $19 : 10$, and thus, this is the solution.
